# Movie Stream AWS Kubernetes Deployment

This deployment creates an EKS-based environment for:

- `movie-gateway`
- `movies-api`
- `movies-ui`
- PostgreSQL for the movie catalog
- PostgreSQL for Keycloak
- Keycloak
- pgAdmin
- AWS ALB ingress with HTTPS

Secrets and deploy-time values live in `deployment/.env.prod`, which is ignored by Git. Kubernetes Secrets and ConfigMaps are generated by `deployment/start.sh`; secret values are not stored in Kubernetes YAML files.

## Prerequisites

Install and configure:

- AWS CLI authenticated to the target AWS account
- Terraform `>= 1.6`
- `kubectl`
- Docker
- `envsubst`; on macOS: `brew install gettext`
- GitHub token with GHCR package read/write permissions
- A public domain or subdomain, for example `movies.example.com`
- Route 53 hosted zone for the domain, or access to your external DNS provider

The deployment region and stateful availability zone are configured in `deployment/infra/terraform.auto.tfvars`.

```hcl
# deployment/infra/terraform.auto.tfvars
aws_region                 = "eu-central-1"
name_prefix                = "movie-stream"
stateful_availability_zone = "eu-central-1a"
```

## 1. Create `deployment/.env.prod`

```bash
cp deployment/.env.prod.example deployment/.env.prod
```

Edit `deployment/.env.prod`.

Required registry values:

```bash
DOCKER_SERVER=ghcr.io
CONTAINER_REGISTRY=ghcr.io/<github-user-or-org>
GITHUB_USERNAME=<github-user>
GITHUB_TOKEN=<github-token-with-package-write>
IMAGE_VERSION=1.2.0-movie-challenge
```

Required AWS and app values:

```bash
AWS_REGION=eu-central-1
INFRA_NAME_PREFIX=movie-stream
STATEFUL_AVAILABILITY_ZONE=eu-central-1a

APP_NAMESPACE=movie-stream
APP_DOMAIN=movies.example.com
APP_BASE_URL=https://movies.example.com
KEYCLOAK_DOMAIN=keycloak.movies.example.com
KEYCLOAK_EXTERNAL_URL=https://keycloak.movies.example.com
AWS_ACM_CERTIFICATE_ARN=<filled-after-certificate-step>
```

Required database and admin values:

```bash
MOVIES_JDBC_URL=jdbc:postgresql://movies-postgres:5432/movies
MOVIES_JDBC_USERNAME=movies
MOVIES_JDBC_PASSWORD=<secure-password>

KEYCLOAK_POSTGRES_DB=keycloak
KEYCLOAK_POSTGRES_USER=keycloak
KEYCLOAK_POSTGRES_PASSWORD=<secure-password>
KEYCLOAK_ADMIN=admin
KEYCLOAK_ADMIN_PASSWORD=<secure-password>

PGADMIN_DEFAULT_EMAIL=admin@movies.example.com
PGADMIN_DEFAULT_PASSWORD=<secure-password>

OMDB_API_KEY=<your-omdb-api-key>
```

Leave the EBS volume IDs empty until step 4 if you have not created or found them yet.

## 2. Publish Docker Images

Build and publish the deployment images:

```bash
./deployment/docker-publish.sh
```

The default version is `1.2.0-movie-challenge`, so the script publishes:

```text
ghcr.io/<github-user-or-org>/movie-gateway:1.2.0-movie-challenge
ghcr.io/<github-user-or-org>/movies-api:1.2.0-movie-challenge
ghcr.io/<github-user-or-org>/movies-ui:1.2.0-movie-challenge
```

## 3. Create AWS Infrastructure

Create the VPC, EKS cluster, EBS CSI driver, `ebs-sc` storage class, AWS Load Balancer Controller, and a small node group pinned to `STATEFUL_AVAILABILITY_ZONE`:

```bash
./deployment/start.sh infra
```

The script prints the stateful AZ and subnet:

```text
Stateful AZ: eu-central-1a
Stateful subnet ID: subnet-...
```

Your pre-created EBS volumes must be in the same AZ as the stateful node group.

## 4. Prepare EBS gp3 Volumes

This deployment uses the same persistence style as `movie-votes`: static Kubernetes PersistentVolumes pointing at pre-created EBS volumes, with `persistentVolumeReclaimPolicy: Retain`.

EBS volumes are region and AZ scoped. They are not inside a VPC, so an old volume can be reused by a new EKS cluster if it is in the same AWS account, same region, and same AZ as a worker node.

### Option A: Reuse Existing Volumes

Find existing gp3 volumes in Frankfurt:

```bash
aws ec2 describe-volumes \
  --region eu-central-1 \
  --filters Name=volume-type,Values=gp3 \
  --query 'Volumes[*].{Id:VolumeId,SizeGiB:Size,AZ:AvailabilityZone,State:State,Name:Tags[?Key==`Name`]|[0].Value}' \
  --output table
```

Look for the `70 GiB` movie database volume from your old deployment. It should look like `vol-...`.

Confirm the volume is in `eu-central-1a`:

```bash
aws ec2 describe-volumes \
  --region eu-central-1 \
  --volume-ids vol-0123456789abcdef0 \
  --query 'Volumes[0].{Id:VolumeId,SizeGiB:Size,AZ:AvailabilityZone,State:State,Type:VolumeType}' \
  --output table
```

If the volume is attached to an old EC2 instance, stop the old workload and detach it before reusing it.

### Option B: Create New Volumes

Create a 70 GiB gp3 volume for the movie catalog database:

```bash
aws ec2 create-volume \
  --region eu-central-1 \
  --availability-zone eu-central-1a \
  --volume-type gp3 \
  --size 70 \
  --encrypted \
  --tag-specifications 'ResourceType=volume,Tags=[{Key=Name,Value=movie-stream-movies-postgres},{Key=Project,Value=movie-stream-workshop}]'
```

Create a smaller gp3 volume for Keycloak Postgres:

```bash
aws ec2 create-volume \
  --region eu-central-1 \
  --availability-zone eu-central-1a \
  --volume-type gp3 \
  --size 10 \
  --encrypted \
  --tag-specifications 'ResourceType=volume,Tags=[{Key=Name,Value=movie-stream-keycloak-postgres},{Key=Project,Value=movie-stream-workshop}]'
```

Wait until both volumes are `available`:

```bash
aws ec2 describe-volumes \
  --region eu-central-1 \
  --volume-ids vol-... vol-... \
  --query 'Volumes[*].{Id:VolumeId,SizeGiB:Size,AZ:AvailabilityZone,State:State,Type:VolumeType}' \
  --output table
```

Add the IDs to `deployment/.env.prod`:

```bash
MOVIES_POSTGRES_VOLUME_ID=vol-0123456789abcdef0
MOVIES_POSTGRES_VOLUME_AZ=eu-central-1a
MOVIES_POSTGRES_STORAGE_SIZE=70Gi

KEYCLOAK_POSTGRES_VOLUME_ID=vol-0123456789abcdef1
KEYCLOAK_POSTGRES_VOLUME_AZ=eu-central-1a
KEYCLOAK_POSTGRES_STORAGE_SIZE=10Gi
```

Do not delete these volumes during cleanup unless you intentionally want to delete the database data.

## 5. Prepare HTTPS Certificate

The Kubernetes ingress uses AWS Load Balancer Controller and terminates HTTPS with an ACM certificate:

```bash
AWS_ACM_CERTIFICATE_ARN=arn:aws:acm:eu-central-1:<account-id>:certificate/<id>
```

You can use either an ACM-issued public certificate or a Let's Encrypt certificate imported into ACM.

### Option A: ACM Public Certificate

1. Open AWS Certificate Manager in `eu-central-1`.
2. Choose **Request certificate**.
3. Choose **Request a public certificate**.
4. Add both `APP_DOMAIN` and `KEYCLOAK_DOMAIN`, for example `movies.example.com` and `keycloak.movies.example.com`.
5. Choose **DNS validation**.
6. If the domain is hosted in Route 53 in the same account, choose **Create records in Route 53**.
7. If DNS is outside Route 53, copy the ACM validation CNAME record to your DNS provider.
8. Wait until the certificate status is **Issued**.
9. Copy the certificate ARN to `AWS_ACM_CERTIFICATE_ARN` in `deployment/.env.prod`.

### Option B: Let's Encrypt Imported Into ACM

Use this if you already prefer Let's Encrypt. The ALB still needs the certificate inside ACM.

Create or renew the certificate with a DNS challenge:

```bash
sudo certbot certonly \
  --manual \
  --preferred-challenges dns \
  -d movies.example.com \
  -d keycloak.movies.example.com
```

Follow certbot's instructions and create the required DNS TXT record. After issuance, import the certificate into ACM:

```bash
aws acm import-certificate \
  --region eu-central-1 \
  --certificate fileb:///etc/letsencrypt/live/movies.example.com/cert.pem \
  --private-key fileb:///etc/letsencrypt/live/movies.example.com/privkey.pem \
  --certificate-chain fileb:///etc/letsencrypt/live/movies.example.com/chain.pem \
  --query CertificateArn \
  --output text
```

Put the returned ARN into `deployment/.env.prod`:

```bash
AWS_ACM_CERTIFICATE_ARN=arn:aws:acm:eu-central-1:<account-id>:certificate/<id>
```

Imported Let's Encrypt certificates do not automatically renew in ACM. Renew with certbot and re-import before expiry.

## 6. Deploy Kubernetes Resources

Deploy the application:

```bash
./deployment/start.sh app
```

This creates:

- namespace
- GHCR image pull secret
- application Secrets and ConfigMaps
- static EBS-backed Postgres PersistentVolumes and PVCs
- movie catalog Postgres StatefulSet
- Keycloak Postgres StatefulSet
- Keycloak with the local `movies` realm defaults
- `movies-api`
- `movie-gateway`
- `movies-ui`
- pgAdmin
- AWS ALB ingress with ACM TLS

Check rollout status:

```bash
kubectl -n movie-stream get pods
kubectl -n movie-stream get pvc
kubectl -n movie-stream get ingress movie-stream
```

## 7. Configure Route 53 For The ALB

After `./deployment/start.sh app`, get the ALB DNS name:

```bash
kubectl -n movie-stream get ingress movie-stream \
  -o jsonpath='{.status.loadBalancer.ingress[0].hostname}{"\n"}'
```

In Route 53:

1. Open the hosted zone for your domain.
2. Choose **Create record**.
3. Set **Record name** to the subdomain from `APP_DOMAIN`, for example `movies`.
4. Set **Record type** to `A`.
5. Enable **Alias**.
6. Choose **Alias to Application and Classic Load Balancer**.
7. Choose region `eu-central-1`.
8. Select the ALB created by the Kubernetes ingress.
9. Create the record.

Create the same kind of record for `KEYCLOAK_DOMAIN`, for example `keycloak.movies`.

Both records point to the same ALB. The ingress uses host rules to send `APP_DOMAIN` to the application and `KEYCLOAK_DOMAIN` to Keycloak.

If Route 53 does not list the ALB yet, wait a few minutes or paste the ALB DNS name manually. For a subdomain, a CNAME to the ALB DNS name also works. For a root/apex domain, use an A alias record.

Verify DNS and HTTPS:

```bash
dig +short movies.example.com
curl -I https://movies.example.com
```

URLs:

```text
Application: https://movies.example.com
Keycloak:    https://keycloak.movies.example.com
pgAdmin:     https://movies.example.com/pgadmin
```

Keycloak is publicly reachable through the ALB at `KEYCLOAK_EXTERNAL_URL`. The admin console is password protected by `KEYCLOAK_ADMIN` and `KEYCLOAK_ADMIN_PASSWORD`.

The deployment keeps the same Keycloak defaults as the local setup:

```text
Realm:              movies
UI client:          movies-ui
API audience:       movies-api
```

The backend services use the internal Kubernetes URLs by default:

```text
KEYCLOAK_ISSUER_URI=http://keycloak:8080/realms/movies
KEYCLOAK_TOKEN_URI=http://keycloak:8080/realms/movies/protocol/openid-connect/token
```

The browser-facing URL differs from local and is configured with:

```text
KEYCLOAK_EXTERNAL_URL=https://keycloak.movies.example.com
```

pgAdmin is publicly reachable through the ALB at `/pgadmin`. The pgAdmin login page is password protected by `PGADMIN_DEFAULT_EMAIL` and `PGADMIN_DEFAULT_PASSWORD`.

In pgAdmin, connect to the movie database with:

```text
Host: movies-postgres
Port: 5432
Database: database name from MOVIES_JDBC_URL
Username: value of MOVIES_JDBC_USERNAME
Password: value of MOVIES_JDBC_PASSWORD
```

## One Command Path

If images, EBS volumes, ACM certificate, and `.env.prod` are already ready:

```bash
./deployment/start.sh
```

For a first deployment, the safer staged flow is:

```bash
./deployment/start.sh infra
./deployment/docker-publish.sh
./deployment/start.sh app
```

Then create or update the Route 53 record.

## Destroy

Destroy Kubernetes resources and Terraform-managed infrastructure:

```bash
./deployment/destroy.sh
```

The destroy script deletes the ingress first so AWS load balancers are removed before Terraform destroys the VPC. It then deletes the namespace and static PV objects and destroys Terraform infrastructure.

The external EBS volumes are not managed by Terraform and are not deleted. They remain available for a future deployment.

## Troubleshooting

If a Postgres pod is pending, check that the EBS volume AZ matches the pod node affinity:

```bash
kubectl -n movie-stream describe pod -l app.kubernetes.io/name=movies-postgres
kubectl describe pv movies-postgres-ebs-pv
aws ec2 describe-volumes --region eu-central-1 --volume-ids "$MOVIES_POSTGRES_VOLUME_ID"
```

If the certificate is not issued, check the ACM DNS validation CNAME record in Route 53 or your DNS provider.

If the ingress has no hostname, check the AWS Load Balancer Controller:

```bash
kubectl -n kube-system logs deployment/aws-load-balancer-controller
kubectl -n movie-stream describe ingress movie-stream
```

## References

- AWS ACM DNS validation: https://docs.aws.amazon.com/acm/latest/userguide/dns-validation.html
- Route 53 alias records for load balancers: https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/routing-to-elb-load-balancer.html
- AWS EBS CSI driver parameters: https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/aws-ebs-csi-driver/blob/master/docs/parameters.md
